Boil a #kettle{}. Peel and finely chop the @red onion{1/2}(finely chopped), @garlic clove{1}(finely chopped) and @parsley{3%sprigs}(finely chopped). Finely chop the @tarragon{3}(finely chopped). Thinly slice the @wild mushrooms{1}(thinly sliced). Mix half the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} with 120ml of your boiling water in a #jug{} and stir to dissolve.

Heat a large #frying pan{} over a medium heat and add @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Once warm, add the onion and sweat for ~{2-3%minutes} until translucent. Add the garlic and mushrooms and season with @salt{1/4%tsp} and @ground black pepper{a few grinds}. Cook for a few mins until the mushrooms are cooked through, then turn heat to low.

Meanwhile, bring a large #pot{} of water to the boil for the pasta and add @salt{1/4%tsp}. Cook your @wheat tagliatelle{220%g} in the boiling water for around ~{10%minutes} or until 'al dente'.

> "Al dente" means the pasta is cooked through but has a hint of firmness left in the middle.

Sprinkle the @flour{1/2%tsp} over the mushrooms and stir gently until it has been absorbed. Add the vegetable stock, parsley and tarragon to the pan. Simmer gently until thickened (about ~{3%minutes}). Add a few tbsp of the pasta water to loosen it up.

Finish the sauce by stirring in the @crème fraîche{1}. Add a good squeeze of @lemon{1/2}(juiced) and a couple more twists of black pepper. Cook gently for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Drain the pasta and add to the pan with the sauce.

Serve in bowls with your @grated hard Italian style cheese{2%tbsp} sprinkled over the top.